## ðŸ“‹ SOLID PRINCIPLES CHECKLIST

### Single Responsibility Principle
- [ ] âœ… Each class has exactly one reason to change
- [ ] âœ… Each method has a single, well-defined purpose
- [ ] âœ… Classes are focused on one business concern
- [ ] âœ… No "god classes" with multiple responsibilities

### Open-Closed Principle  
- [ ] âœ… Classes are closed for modification
- [ ] âœ… Classes are open for extension via inheritance/composition
- [ ] âœ… New features added without changing existing code
- [ ] âœ… Abstract base classes define extension points

### Liskov Substitution Principle
- [ ] âœ… Subtypes are substitutable for base types
- [ ] âœ… Method signatures match exactly
- [ ] âœ… Behavioral contracts are maintained
- [ ] âœ… No strengthened preconditions or weakened postconditions

### Interface Segregation Principle
- [ ] âœ… Interfaces are small and focused
- [ ] âœ… Clients depend only on methods they use
- [ ] âœ… No "fat interfaces" with unrelated methods
- [ ] âœ… Interface cohesion is high

### Dependency Inversion Principle
- [ ] âœ… High-level modules depend on abstractions
- [ ] âœ… Low-level modules implement abstractions
- [ ] âœ… Dependencies injected at composition root
- [ ] âœ… No concrete dependencies in business logic

Remember: **SOLID principles are not optional guidelines - they are MANDATORY requirements.** Every violation makes the codebase harder to maintain, test, and extend. Design for change from the beginning.